dotnet/aspire#15108.body:
Code like the following will deadlock the apphost:

```ts
const mobileBff = await builder.addYarp("mobile-bff")
    .withExternalHttpEndpoints()
    // Configure YARP routes for mobile BFF
    .withConfiguration(async (yarp) => {
        const redisEndpoint = await redis.getEndpoint("http");
```

The reason is because withConfiguration looks like this on the C# side:

https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/blob/5b9f8167456454515a463693f8661c1abe7e07a6/src/Aspire.Hosting.Yarp/YarpResourceExtensions.cs#L106-L112

Because the `configurationBuilder` callback is invoked directly inline, the AppHost gets deadlocked.

   - RPC call invoked the callback inline
   - outer invokeCapability("withConfiguration") was still active
   - sync callback bridge blocked waiting for TS
   - TS callback called back into host with getEndpoint
   - that re-entrancy is what deadlocked

Looking over the code base, we have this pattern in the following as well:

Same risk class as old YARP: exported sync Action... callback, invoked inline.

   - RunAsEmulator / RunAsContainer: AppConfig, Azure SQL, Azure Managed Redis, Azure PostgreSQL, Event Hubs, SignalR, Storage, Cosmos DB, Service Bus, Kusto
   - WithMongoExpress, WithAttu, WithKafkaUI, WithPhpMyAdmin, WithPgAdmin, WithPgWeb, WithPostgresMcp, WithRedisCommander, WithRedisInsight, Docker Compose configureDashboard
   - WithProperties: Azure OpenAI, Event Hub, Service Bus queue/topic/subscription, Docker Compose env, Kubernetes env
   - PublishAsAzureAppServiceWebsite
   - PublishAsAzureContainerApp* / ...Job
   - PublishAsDockerComposeService
   - PublishAsDockerFileWithConfigure (project/executable)
   - PublishAsKubernetesService
   - AddProjectWithOptions
   - AddCSharpAppWithOptions
   - AddConnectionStringBuilder

## Possible Solution 1: Fix what is exported

One fix is to update all these callsites with new overloads that take a `Func<X, Task>` and expose that instead:

```C#
    public static IResourceBuilder<YarpResource> WithConfiguration(this IResourceBuilder<YarpResource> builder, Action<IYarpConfigurationBuilder> configurationBuilder)
    {
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(builder);
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(configurationBuilder);

        var configBuilder = new YarpConfigurationBuilder(builder);
        configurationBuilder(configBuilder);

        return builder;
    }

    [AspireExport("withConfiguration", Description = "Configure the YARP resource.")]
    internal static async Task<IResourceBuilder<YarpResource>> WithConfigurationInternal(this IResourceBuilder<YarpResource> builder, Func<IYarpConfigurationBuilder, Task> configurationBuilder)
    {
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(builder);
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(configurationBuilder);

        var configBuilder = new YarpConfigurationBuilder(builder);
        await configurationBuilder(configBuilder).ConfigureAwait(false);

        return builder;
    }
```

If we make this fix, we should also update the analyzer to catch these coding patterns.

## Possible Solution 2: Fix the pattern in the interop code

Instead of forcing the integration author's to update their code, we could wrap the invocation of the callback in a `Task.Run(() => callback())`, which would allow us to support this pattern.

