### Describe the bug

In an `apphost.ts` file, imagine that you have the following code:

```ts
// Aspire TypeScript AppHost
// For more information, see: https://aspire.dev

import { ContainerLifetime, createBuilder, IconVariant, } from "./.modules/aspire.js";
import { Client } from "pg";

const builder = await createBuilder();

const postgres = await builder
  .addPostgres("postgres")
  .withDataVolume()
  .withLifetime(ContainerLifetime.Persistent);

const db = await postgres.addDatabase("todos-db");

await db.withCommand(
  "clear-database",
  "Clear database",
  async (context) => {
    const cancellationToken = await context.cancellationToken.get();
    const connectionStringExpression = await db.uriExpression.get();
    const connectionString = await connectionStringExpression.getValue(cancellationToken);
    if (!connectionString) {
      return { success: false, error: "Failed to get database connection string" };
    }

    const client = new Client({ connectionString });

    try {
      await client.connect();

      // Omitted for brevity...

      return { success: true };
    } catch (e) {
      return { success: false, error: e instanceof Error ? e.message : "Failed to clear database" };
    } finally {
      await client.end();
    }
  }
);

await builder.build().run();
```

Specifically, the flow of the callback, when given a `context` exposes as `cancellationToken` it's from the server AppHost. Currently, this isn't supported. When we attempt to use the token to pass into the `getValue` API we pass the resolved token - but ultimately receive this error:

```txt
Executing command 'clear-database'.
 Error executing command 'clear-database'.
StreamJsonRpc.RemoteInvocationException: Request invokeCallback failed with message: Callback execution failed: Serialization and deserialization of 'System.IntPtr' instances is not supported. Path: $.WaitHandle.Handle.
   at StreamJsonRpc.JsonRpc.InvokeCoreAsync[TResult](RequestId id, String targetName, IReadOnlyList`1 arguments, IReadOnlyList`1 positionalArgumentDeclaredTypes, IReadOnlyDictionary`2 namedArgumentDeclaredTypes, CancellationToken cancellationToken, Boolean isParameterObject)
   at Aspire.Hosting.RemoteHost.JsonRpcCallbackInvoker.InvokeAsync[TResult](String callbackId, JsonNode args, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at Aspire.Hosting.RemoteHost.Ats.AtsCallbackProxyFactory.InvokeAsyncResult[T](String callbackId, JsonObject args, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at Aspire.Hosting.ApplicationModel.ResourceCommandService.ExecuteCommandCoreAsync(String resourceId, IResource resource, String commandName, CancellationToken cancellationToken) in D:\GitHub\aspire\src\Aspire.Hosting\ApplicationModel\ResourceCommandService.cs:line 161
```

### Expected Behavior

While hypothetically speaking, one might assume this would just work (since it does in C#), it's not something that's really been fully designed/implemented.

As a work around, we can fake the signal by creating an `AbortSignal` from TS and then passing it instead, but this doesn't actually work either:

```ts
const cancellationToken = AbortSignal.timeout(1); // 1 ms timeout to show issue
const connectionStringExpression = await db.uriExpression.get();
const connectionString = await connectionStringExpression.getValue(cancellationToken);
if (!connectionString) {
  return { success: false, error: "Failed to get database connection string" };
}

const client = new Client({ connectionString });
```

> [!WARNING]
> This signal doesn't work.

```txt
Executing command 'clear-database'.
 Error executing command 'clear-database'.
StreamJsonRpc.RemoteInvocationException: Request invokeCallback failed with message: Callback execution failed: Missing required argument 'cancellationToken'
   at StreamJsonRpc.JsonRpc.InvokeCoreAsync[TResult](RequestId id, String targetName, IReadOnlyList`1 arguments, IReadOnlyList`1 positionalArgumentDeclaredTypes, IReadOnlyDictionary`2 namedArgumentDeclaredTypes, CancellationToken cancellationToken, Boolean isParameterObject)
